27
00:02:13.280 --> 00:02:15.220
to be their whipping boys.

28
00:02:15.220 --> 00:02:16.640
And we’re gonna get to that...

29
00:02:16.640 --> 00:03:08.909
But first, let’s have a look at China’s
odd, winding journey into the film industry.

30
00:03:08.909 --> 00:03:12.829
So the first thing we need to talk about is
the box office, and how much money movies

31
00:03:12.829 --> 00:03:14.360
make while in theatres.

32
00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:18.490
When studios report the projected box office
earnings of any given movie, usually on Sunday

33
00:03:18.490 --> 00:03:22.860
but sometimes on Monday if it’s a long weekend,
you’ll see the gross amount the movie made

34
00:03:22.860 --> 00:03:25.159
by selling tickets at movie theatres.

35
00:03:25.159 --> 00:03:28.269
That number will be broken up into two different
sections.

36
00:03:28.269 --> 00:03:31.319
Domestic, which includes the United States,
Canada.

37
00:03:31.319 --> 00:03:33.870
And International, which is everyone else.

38
00:03:33.870 --> 00:03:36.790
And then they’ll be combined for a Global
gross.

39
00:03:36.790 --> 00:03:39.250
Gross being the most important word here.

40
00:03:39.250 --> 00:03:44.760
In business terms, “gross income” is how
much is made before deductions, “net income”

41
00:03:44.760 --> 00:03:46.819
is how much is made after deductions.

42
00:03:46.819 --> 00:03:51.980
Which, for most people, that means the Net
is how much money you get paid after the government

43
00:03:51.980 --> 00:03:55.450
has taken its taxes, and you’ve paid your
health insurance, and all that.

44
00:03:55.450 --> 00:03:58.350
The gross is always a much nicer number than
that.

45
00:03:58.350 --> 00:04:03.890
Now when it comes to movies, studios never
EVER report the net income because that represents

46
00:04:03.890 --> 00:04:06.400
how much profit is made by the movie.

47
00:04:06.400 --> 00:04:10.530
And if they report the profit made publicly
that leaves them open to things like paying

48
00:04:10.530 --> 00:04:11.569
higher taxes.

49
00:04:11.569 --> 00:04:15.180
A lot of actors also have points on a movie,
which means they get a certain percentage

50
00:04:15.180 --> 00:04:16.280
of the profits.

51
00:04:16.280 --> 00:04:21.210
Jack Nicholson notoriously got points on 1989’s
Batman, and publicly admitted to never having

52
00:04:21.210 --> 00:04:22.590
to work again if he didn't want to.

53
00:04:22.590 --> 00:04:27.240
But that’s not the only reason movie studios
don’t report net revenue from ticket sales.

54
00:04:27.240 --> 00:04:32.450
The other, arguably more important reason,
is they don’t get to keep all of the ticket

55
00:04:32.450 --> 00:04:34.340
sales from the get go.

56
00:04:34.340 --> 00:04:36.080
Movie theatres take a giant chunk of that.

57
00:04:36.080 --> 00:04:40.130
It tends to be different per studio and per
movie, with Disney demanding the highest percentage

58
00:04:40.130 --> 00:04:44.780
of the box office returns, but it works out
to be around 50/50.

59
00:04:44.780 --> 00:04:48.000
Studios will get a higher percentage when
a movie first comes out, and the percentage

60
00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:51.500
will shift into the theatre’s favor the
longer a movie sticks around in cinemas.

61
00:04:51.500 --> 00:04:54.630
So sometimes it’s not exactly 50/50, but
that’s the average.

62
00:04:54.630 --> 00:04:58.090
And that’s not even getting into the fact
that marketing and distribution costs aren’t

63
00:04:58.090 --> 00:04:59.900
calcuated into that figure.

64
00:04:59.900 --> 00:05:04.330
Some movies have advertising campaigns that
cost as much as their production budget so

65
00:05:04.330 --> 00:05:08.240
they’d need to make 4 times their budget
before they make a profit.

66
00:05:08.240 --> 00:05:12.290
It can get so complicated that it’s no wonder
there’s an actual industry term called “Hollywood

67
00:05:12.290 --> 00:05:13.290
Accounting.”

68
00:05:13.290 --> 00:05:17.229
Yeah it’s mostly to hide money from the
government and people with profit participation,

69
00:05:17.229 --> 00:05:21.009
but it’s also because you need to be a special
kind of accountant to wrap your head around

70
00:05:21.009 --> 00:05:22.009
this whole thing.

71
00:05:22.009 --> 00:05:23.540
And that’s just the studio side of it.

72
00:05:23.540 --> 00:05:25.530
The theatre side can get complicated too.

73
00:05:25.530 --> 00:05:28.759
That’s why you’ll see a lot of theatre
chains have special popcorn buckets and soda

74
00:05:28.759 --> 00:05:31.569
cups available for big new movies on opening
weekend.

75
00:05:31.569 --> 00:05:33.000
And charge a surcharge for them.

76
00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:37.020
They want you to buy these things, which they
put a giant mark up on, so that they can bring

77
00:05:37.020 --> 00:05:42.139
in more revenue at a time when any given movie’s
ticket sales will be mostly going to the studio.

78
00:05:42.139 --> 00:05:46.590
Some theatres, before the days of Covid anyway,
would also charge extra for assigned seating.

79
00:05:46.590 --> 00:05:50.470
That extra money would go exclusively to the
theatre, since they’re charging a convenience

80
00:05:50.470 --> 00:05:54.020
fee on top of the initial fee to see the movie.

81
00:05:54.020 --> 00:05:58.419
And this has been the way that Hollywood worked
for a really long time.

82
00:05:58.419 --> 00:06:01.770
Ever since the supreme court decided that
movie studios were no longer allowed to own

83
00:06:01.770 --> 00:06:02.770
theatre chains.

84
00:06:02.770 --> 00:06:05.120
Which was a big thing back in the day.

85
00:06:05.120 --> 00:06:08.830
Studios would own whole theatre chains and
only show their movies there.

86
00:06:08.830 --> 00:06:12.789
So if you lived in a small town and your local
theatre was owned by Paramount but a Fox movie

87
00:06:12.789 --> 00:06:16.690
was coming out that you really wanted to see,
well, you were shit out of luck.

88
00:06:16.690 --> 00:06:19.370
Better hope it ends up in a second run theatre
in a few years.

89
00:06:19.370 --> 00:06:24.259
But then, in the case of The United States
v. Paramount Pictures in 1948, it was decided

90
00:06:24.259 --> 00:06:28.930
that studios could no longer own theatres
and so this new 50/50 split was eventually

91
00:06:28.930 --> 00:06:30.020
worked out.

92
00:06:30.020 --> 00:06:34.539
This will be changing soon though since the
Justice Department under the former Trump

93
00:06:34.539 --> 00:06:39.800
administration decided to toss out the Paramount
Decrees so in August of 2022 Disney will be

94
00:06:39.800 --> 00:06:42.710
allowed to buy as many theatres in the United
States as it wants.

95
00:06:42.710 --> 00:06:46.050
But, for now, that 50/50 is still in effect.

96
00:06:46.050 --> 00:06:47.580
And it’s all across the globe.

97
00:06:47.580 --> 00:06:51.250
Europe, South America, Australia, and most
of Asia works under the same principle.

98
00:06:51.250 --> 00:06:54.699
But then a fly landed in the ointment and
started messing things up.

99
00:06:54.699 --> 00:06:57.540
A gigantic fly called China.

100
00:06:57.540 --> 00:07:02.330
Filmmaking had taken off in China in the 1930s
when Chinese filmmakers, sick and tired of

101
00:07:02.330 --> 00:07:06.300
Hollywood’s racist and offensive depictions
of the Chinese people, began making their

102
00:07:06.300 --> 00:07:07.500
own feature films.

103
00:07:07.500 --> 00:07:11.879
But After the communist revolution of 1949,
domestic films that were already released

104
00:07:11.879 --> 00:07:14.530
and a selection of foreign films were banned.

105
00:07:14.530 --> 00:07:17.570
Despite this though, movie attendance increased
sharply.

106
00:07:17.570 --> 00:07:22.289
But then during the Cultural Revolution, the
film industry was severely restricted, coming

107
00:07:22.289 --> 00:07:25.979
almost to a standstill from 1967 to 1972.

108
00:07:25.979 --> 00:07:30.289
But in the years immediately following the
Cultural Revolution, the film industry flourished

109
00:07:30.289 --> 00:07:32.500
as a medium of popular entertainment.

110
00:07:32.500 --> 00:07:38.690
Production rose steadily, from 19 movies in
1977 to 125 movies in 1986.

111
00:07:38.690 --> 00:07:43.110
And the numbers of films just kept rising
from there, though a pretty big chunk of the

112
00:07:43.110 --> 00:07:46.740
movies released were actually propaganda films
financed by the Chinese government.

113
00:07:46.740 --> 00:07:50.970
Following the international commercial success
of films like Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon

114
00:07:50.970 --> 00:07:56.550
and Hero, Hollywood started to take notice
of the growing power of the Chinese market.

115
00:07:56.550 --> 00:08:00.699
And so they began a campaign to have more
and more Hollywood movies released in China,

116
00:08:00.699 --> 00:08:05.070
which the government at the time was more
than willing to let happen because it helped

117
00:08:05.070 --> 00:08:09.340
the nation feel further legitimized by the
international community.

118
00:08:09.340 --> 00:08:12.389
China wasn’t a communist backwater nation
like North Korea.

119
00:08:12.389 --> 00:08:16.830
It was a growing economy with happy citizens
who wanted to enjoy films from all over the

120
00:08:16.830 --> 00:08:18.099
world.

121
00:08:18.099 --> 00:08:22.070
How happy their citizens really were is up
for debate but that’s the narrative the

122
00:08:22.070 --> 00:08:23.780
Chinese government propagated.

123
00:08:23.780 --> 00:08:28.419
At first Hollywood was actually able to negotiate
pretty good terms with the country.

124
00:08:28.419 --> 00:08:33.699
Something closer to a 40/60 split, with Hollywood
studios getting 60% of the box office returns.

125
00:08:33.699 --> 00:08:39.039
But as the Chinese box office began growing
year over year, the Chinese government began

126
00:08:39.039 --> 00:08:44.030
to renege on those agreements, forcing studios
back to the negotiating table, sometimes twice

127
00:08:44.030 --> 00:08:45.130
a year.

128
00:08:45.130 --> 00:08:49.110
Whereas studios would sign decade long contracts
with American theatre chains.

129
00:08:49.110 --> 00:08:55.490
All of this lead to today, where China reportedly
keeps a whopping 75-80% of the box office

130
00:08:55.490 --> 00:08:56.490
returns.

131
00:08:56.490 --> 00:08:57.900
With studios getting as little as 20%.

132
00:08:57.900 --> 00:09:03.020
There’s no public financial data for representing
this because, again, studios like to keep

133
00:09:03.020 --> 00:09:07.650
how much their movies make, and where that
money comes from, as secret as possible.

134
00:09:07.650 --> 00:09:10.190
Lest they be forced to pay their share of
taxes.

135
00:09:10.190 --> 00:09:14.170
But people in the industry who work on the
financial side of things seem to have loose

136
00:09:14.170 --> 00:09:18.440
lips, and they’re more than happy to talk
about how China is screwing over an American

137
00:09:18.440 --> 00:09:19.440
industry.

138
00:09:19.440 --> 00:09:21.839
Now 20% is better than nothing, right?

139
00:09:21.839 --> 00:09:28.520
Avengers Endgame made $629 million in China,
so 20% of that is about 126 million.

140
00:09:28.520 --> 00:09:30.279
Nothing to sneeze at.

141
00:09:30.279 --> 00:09:35.050
It’s not the 315 million Disney would have
gotten under a 50/50 agreement but it’s

142
00:09:35.050 --> 00:09:36.050
not nothing!

143
00:09:36.050 --> 00:09:39.200
But Endgame may have made even more money
in China.

144
00:09:39.200 --> 00:09:43.029
See, Chinese theatre chains have been known
to be a bit sneaky.

145
00:09:43.029 --> 00:09:47.279
Tourists visiting the country and going to
see movies while there have seen ticket sellers

146
00:09:47.279 --> 00:09:51.570
take your money for a Hollywood movie, ring
up the sale as a ticket for a Chinese propaganda

147
00:09:51.570 --> 00:09:53.690
film, and then wave you on through.

148
00:09:53.690 --> 00:09:57.950
These reports are all independent, and there’s
no financial data reporting this, again, so

149
00:09:57.950 --> 00:10:02.200
take it with a grain of salt, but it seems
to be reported... a lot.

150
00:10:02.200 --> 00:10:05.640
In fact a lot of people who work in the industry
are pretty convinced that China fudges their

151
00:10:05.640 --> 00:10:07.360
numbers all the time.

152
00:10:07.360 --> 00:10:11.550
Avengers Endgame had been the biggest opening
weekend of all time at a domestic box office,

153
00:10:11.550 --> 00:10:14.230
with 357 million dollars in the US, and Canada.

154
00:10:14.230 --> 00:10:19.380
A record most industry professionals were
convinced wouldn’t be broken for years.

155
00:10:19.380 --> 00:10:24.880
But then, earlier this year, Detective Chinatown
3 opened in China to a reported opening weekend

